To replace the platform header with your tenant's branded header:

```ts
await fetch('/v1/runtime/zones/header', {
  method: 'PUT',
  headers: {'Authorization': `Bearer ${token}`, 'Content-Type': 'application/json'},
  body: JSON.stringify({
    replacement: {
      kind: 'full',
      component_ref: 'tenant-acme/HeaderShell@1.4.0',
      props: {branding_tier: 'corporate'}
    }
  })
})
```

The `component_ref` is a module-federation reference — your component must be served from an origin in the tenant-trusted-origins allow-list (configured at tenant onboarding). The platform shell loads your component dynamically; if it fails to load, the platform reverts to its default header for that session and emits a runtime-error notification to your admin inbox.

Most tenant customization wants **slot replacement**, not full-zone replacement. Slot replacement keeps the platform's layout, density tokens, and accessibility behaviour — you just supply one component for one slot.

Example: replace the platform's generic search component in the header with a tenant-specific search that knows your domain entities:

```ts
await fetch('/v1/runtime/zones/header/slots/search', {
  method: 'PATCH',
  body: JSON.stringify({
    component_ref: 'tenant-acme/SymbolSearch@2.1.0',
    audience_segment: 'fixed-income-traders'
  })
})
```

The `audience_segment` makes this slot replacement conditional — only members of `fixed-income-traders` see the tenant's symbol-search; everyone else gets the platform default. Define audiences via `POST /v1/runtime/audiences`.

Audiences are predicates over the caller's identity claims. They drive both runtime config resolution (which zone/slot replacement wins) and entitlement grants.

```json
POST /v1/runtime/audiences
{
  "name": "fixed-income-traders",
  "description": "Users who hold a trader role and are in the fixed-income desk org unit.",
  "match": {
    "all": [
      {"claim": "roles", "contains": "trader"},
      {"claim": "org_unit", "in": ["fixed-income", "credit-trading"]}
    ]
  }
}
```

Entitlements name what a user can do. They're granted to one or more audiences:

```json
POST /v1/runtime/entitlements
{
  "name": "view_order_book",
  "description": "Can view the institutional order book.",
  "granted_to_audiences": ["fixed-income-traders", "compliance-officers"]
}
```

In the SDK, check entitlements client-side: `await webSdk.runtime.hasEntitlement('view_order_book')`. The check evaluates against the user's cached identity — no extra round-trip.

Menus are trees of items, with each item optionally gated by an audience segment or an entitlement. The runtime returns only items the caller is allowed to see — your app doesn't need to filter client-side.

```json
PUT /v1/runtime/menus/main
{
  "name": "main",
  "anchor": "primary-nav",
  "items": [
    {"label": "Dashboard", "href": "/dashboard"},
    {"label": "Trade", "href": "/trade", "required_entitlement": "submit_orders"},
    {"label": "Admin", "href": "/admin", "audience_segment": "tenant-admins",
     "children": [
       {"label": "Users", "href": "/admin/users"},
       {"label": "Audit", "href": "/admin/audit", "required_entitlement": "read_audit_log"}
     ]}
  ]
}
```

The rendered menu adapts per user: a non-admin sees just Dashboard + Trade (if entitled); an admin sees the Admin tree, with Audit hidden unless they have `read_audit_log`.
